1
00:00:01,040 --> 00:00:03,760
My time is running out.

2
00:00:04,280 --> 00:00:07,560
You understand what this is, don't you?

3
00:00:07,960 --> 00:00:12,440
Melody Pond.
The woman who kills the Doctor.

4
00:00:12,560 --> 00:00:16,240
-How do you know who I am?
-I made you what you are.

5
00:00:16,920 --> 00:00:18,880
One last trip, eh?

6
00:00:19,360 --> 00:00:22,200
Whatever happens now,
you do not interfere.

7
00:00:23,520 --> 00:00:27,000
A robot worked by tiny people.

8
00:00:27,200 --> 00:00:29,480
Access personal records, the Doctor.

9
00:00:29,560 --> 00:00:31,080
Records available.

10
00:00:31,160 --> 00:00:33,160
-Who wants me dead?
-The Silence.

11
00:00:33,240 --> 00:00:35,160
The Silence is not a species.

12
00:00:35,240 --> 00:00:37,440
It is a religious order or movement.

13
00:00:37,520 --> 00:00:40,800
Their core belief is that silence
will fall when the question is asked.

14
00:00:40,880 --> 00:00:42,120
What question?

15
00:00:42,200 --> 00:00:45,680
The first question.
The oldest question in the universe.

16
00:00:45,760 --> 00:00:47,320
Hidden in plain sight.

17
00:00:47,400 --> 00:00:49,360
Yes, but what is the question?

18
00:00:52,440 --> 00:00:53,520
Unknown.

19
00:00:57,960 --> 00:00:59,880
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

20
00:00:59,960 --> 00:01:02,080
RADIO ANNOUNCER: And it's another
beautiful day in London.

21
00:01:02,160 --> 00:01:04,880
There are reports of sunspot activity
and solar flares

22
00:01:04,960 --> 00:01:09,040
causing interference across all radio
signals, so apologies for that.

23
00:01:16,120 --> 00:01:17,240
Guys, look!

24
00:01:20,600 --> 00:01:22,520
(CHILDREN SCREAMING)

25
00:01:36,560 --> 00:01:39,160
MAN ON TV: So, do you think you can
top last year's Christmas special?

26
00:01:39,240 --> 00:01:41,120
And can you tell us anything about it?

27
00:01:41,520 --> 00:01:42,520
Well all I can say now

28
00:01:42,600 --> 00:01:46,680
is that it involves ghosts in the past
and the present and the future,

29
00:01:46,760 --> 00:01:47,960
all at the same time.

30
00:01:48,040 --> 00:01:49,760
Oh, we love a ghost story.

31
00:01:49,840 --> 00:01:51,280
(LAUGHING)

32
00:01:51,360 --> 00:01:54,960
Crowds lined the Mall today as the
Holy Roman Emperor, Winston Churchill,

33
00:01:55,160 --> 00:01:58,000
returned to the Buckingham Senate
on his personal mammoth.

34
00:01:58,200 --> 00:02:00,680
Not too many late nights in Gaul,
I hope?

35
00:02:00,760 --> 00:02:01,880
Just the one.

36
00:02:01,960 --> 00:02:04,520
I had an argument with Cleopatra,
dreadful woman.

37
00:02:04,640 --> 00:02:06,440
Oh, excellent dancer.

38
00:02:07,240 --> 00:02:09,360
I can tell from your blood pressure.

39
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:12,680
What time do you have, Doctor?

40
00:02:12,960 --> 00:02:14,960
Two minutes past five, Caesar.

41
00:02:16,680 --> 00:02:19,760
It's always two minutes past five.
Day or night,

42
00:02:20,120 --> 00:02:23,480
it's always two minutes past five
in the afternoon.

43
00:02:24,240 --> 00:02:25,360
Why is that?

44
00:02:25,440 --> 00:02:28,080
-Because that is the time, Caesar.
-And the date.

45
00:02:29,040 --> 00:02:31,240
It's always the 22nd of April.

46
00:02:32,400 --> 00:02:33,920
Does it not bother you?

47
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:36,520
The date and the time
have always been the same, Caesar.

48
00:02:36,600 --> 00:02:38,560
Why should it start bothering me now?

49
00:02:38,640 --> 00:02:40,640
I want to see the soothsayer,
where is he?

50
00:02:40,720 --> 00:02:41,720
In the Tower.

51
00:02:42,120 --> 00:02:44,360
-Where you threw him the last time.
-Get him!

52
00:02:50,520 --> 00:02:51,600
Leave us.

53
00:02:52,880 --> 00:02:55,320
Tick-tock goes the clock.

54
00:02:56,040 --> 00:02:58,160
As the old song says.

55
00:03:01,080 --> 00:03:04,280
But they don't, do they?
The clocks never tick.

56
00:03:04,840 --> 00:03:07,120
Something has happened to time.

57
00:03:07,640 --> 00:03:10,880
That's what you say,
what you never stop saying.

58
00:03:11,320 --> 00:03:13,840
All of history is happening at once.

59
00:03:14,200 --> 00:03:16,080
But what does that mean?

60
00:03:16,640 --> 00:03:17,840
What happened?

61
00:03:18,360 --> 00:03:21,480
Explain to me
in terms that I can understand.

62
00:03:22,040 --> 00:03:24,560
What happened to time?

63
00:03:30,440 --> 00:03:31,440
A woman.

64
00:03:31,520 --> 00:03:33,960
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

65
00:04:08,080 --> 00:04:09,800
DOCTOR: Imagine you were dying.

66
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:15,760
Imagine you were afraid and a long way
from home, and in terrible pain.

67
00:04:16,520 --> 00:04:19,640
Just when you thought
it couldn't get worse,

68
00:04:20,520 --> 00:04:21,800
you looked up

69
00:04:23,600 --> 00:04:26,360
and saw the face of the Devil himself.

70
00:04:31,840 --> 00:04:33,320
Hello, Dalek.

71
00:04:34,200 --> 00:04:38,520
DALEK: Emergency! Emergency!
Weapons system disabled!

72
00:04:38,600 --> 00:04:42,320
(PITCH CHANGING)
Emergency protocol put in place...

73
00:04:42,400 --> 00:04:44,960
Hush now, I need some information
from your data core.

74
00:04:46,360 --> 00:04:49,000
Everything the Daleks know
about the Silence.

75
00:05:06,880 --> 00:05:10,280
Gideon Vandaleur. Get him. Now.

76
00:05:10,680 --> 00:05:12,280
Who says he's here?

77
00:05:23,920 --> 00:05:25,680
Father Gideon Vandaleur.

78
00:05:27,360 --> 00:05:29,560
Former envoy of the Silence.

79
00:05:30,800 --> 00:05:33,880
-(WHISPERING) My condolences.
-Your what?

80
00:05:34,560 --> 00:05:36,720
Gideon Vandaleur has been dead
for six months.

81
00:05:36,800 --> 00:05:39,160
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER BUZZING)

82
00:05:43,200 --> 00:05:44,960
Can I speak to the Captain, please?

83
00:05:46,120 --> 00:05:47,520
DOCTOR: Hello again.

84
00:05:47,600 --> 00:05:50,800
The Tesselecta time-travelling,
shape-changing robot,

85
00:05:50,880 --> 00:05:53,120
powered by miniaturised people.

86
00:05:53,200 --> 00:05:55,680
Never get bored of that.
Long time since Berlin.

87
00:05:55,760 --> 00:05:57,760
Doctor, what have you done
to our systems?

88
00:05:57,840 --> 00:05:59,480
DOCTOR: 04, it'll be fine if you behave.

89
00:05:59,560 --> 00:06:02,160
Now, this unit can disguise itself
as anyone in the universe.

90
00:06:02,240 --> 00:06:05,640
So, if you're posing as Vandaleur,
you're investigating the Silence.

91
00:06:05,760 --> 00:06:06,920
Tell me about them.

92
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:09,400
-Tell you what?
-One thing. Just one.

93
00:06:10,440 --> 00:06:11,720
Their weakest link.

94
00:06:12,200 --> 00:06:13,920
(CROWD SHOUTING)

95
00:06:17,240 --> 00:06:19,200
The crowd are getting restless.

96
00:06:19,280 --> 00:06:21,760
They know the queen
is your only legal move.

97
00:06:22,240 --> 00:06:24,200
Except you've already moved it 12 times,

98
00:06:24,280 --> 00:06:27,760
which means there are now over
four million volts running through it.

99
00:06:27,920 --> 00:06:30,880
(CROWD SHOUTING)

100
00:06:32,600 --> 00:06:34,760
That's why they call it live chess.

101
00:06:34,840 --> 00:06:36,040
(ELECTRICAL BUZZING)

102
00:06:36,120 --> 00:06:39,000
Even with the gauntlet, you'll never
make it to bishop 4 alive.

103
00:06:39,080 --> 00:06:40,640
I am a dead man

104
00:06:41,440 --> 00:06:43,400
unless you concede the game.

105
00:06:43,480 --> 00:06:44,680
But I'm winning.

106
00:06:44,760 --> 00:06:47,200
-Name your price.
-Information.

107
00:06:47,600 --> 00:06:50,520
I work for the Silence.

108
00:06:50,760 --> 00:06:52,600
They would kill me.

109
00:06:52,760 --> 00:06:55,040
They're going to kill me, too,
very soon.

110
00:06:55,400 --> 00:06:58,440
I was just going to lie down
and take it. But you know what?

111
00:06:58,560 --> 00:07:01,840
Before I go, I'd like to know
why I have to die.

112
00:07:02,400 --> 00:07:04,640
Dorium Maldovar.

113
00:07:05,240 --> 00:07:08,320
-He's the only one who can help you.
-Dorium's dead.

114
00:07:08,960 --> 00:07:11,320
-The Monks beheaded him at Demon's Run.
-I know.

115
00:07:11,680 --> 00:07:14,120
Concede the game, Doctor,

116
00:07:15,520 --> 00:07:17,520
and I'll take you to him.

117
00:07:23,920 --> 00:07:25,560
The Seventh Transept.

118
00:07:25,880 --> 00:07:28,200
Where the Headless Monks
keep the leftovers.

119
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:31,440
Watch your step,
there are traps everywhere.

120
00:07:33,840 --> 00:07:35,880
I hate rats.

121
00:07:36,520 --> 00:07:38,880
-There are no rats in the Transept.
-Oh, good.

122
00:07:38,960 --> 00:07:40,480
The skulls eat them.

123
00:07:50,320 --> 00:07:53,120
The Headless Monks behead you alive,

124
00:07:53,200 --> 00:07:54,520
remember?

125
00:07:54,680 --> 00:07:56,760
DOCTOR: Why are some of them in boxes?

126
00:07:57,880 --> 00:07:59,880
Because some people are rich

127
00:08:00,160 --> 00:08:02,920
and some people are left to rot.

128
00:08:03,760 --> 00:08:07,200
And Dorium Maldovar was always

129
00:08:08,080 --> 00:08:09,400
very rich.

130
00:08:13,400 --> 00:08:15,640
(ELECTRICAL BUZZING)

131
00:08:20,760 --> 00:08:22,080
(SNEEZING)

132
00:08:23,520 --> 00:08:25,840
-Thank you for bringing me, Gantok.
-My pleasure.

133
00:08:25,920 --> 00:08:28,840
It saves me the trouble of burying you.

134
00:08:28,920 --> 00:08:30,360
(ELECTRICAL BUZZING)

135
00:08:30,640 --> 00:08:33,920
Nobody beats me at chess.

136
00:08:34,920 --> 00:08:36,480
(SCREAMING)

137
00:08:36,560 --> 00:08:38,080
Gantok!

138
00:08:38,960 --> 00:08:40,840
(SCREAMING)

139
00:08:51,240 --> 00:08:52,360
(HISSING)

140
00:08:54,040 --> 00:08:55,520
(ELECTRICAL BUZZING)

141
00:08:57,800 --> 00:09:00,440
Hello? Is someone there?

142
00:09:02,680 --> 00:09:05,880
Ah, Doctor. Thank God it's you.

143
00:09:06,360 --> 00:09:07,880
The Monks, they turned on me.

144
00:09:07,960 --> 00:09:11,200
Well, I'm afraid they rather did a bit.

145
00:09:11,280 --> 00:09:14,400
Give it to me straight, Doctor.
How bad are my injuries?

146
00:09:14,480 --> 00:09:15,560
Well...

147
00:09:15,640 --> 00:09:17,280
(LAUGHING)

148
00:09:19,120 --> 00:09:21,280
-Oh, your face.
-Yes...

149
00:09:23,920 --> 00:09:26,600
This is absurd. Other worlds?

150
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:30,200
Carnivorous skulls? Talking heads?

151
00:09:30,280 --> 00:09:31,840
I don't know why I'm listening to you.

152
00:09:31,920 --> 00:09:36,120
Because in another reality,
you and I are friends.

153
00:09:36,200 --> 00:09:37,560
And you sense that.

154
00:09:38,560 --> 00:09:41,640
Just as you sense
there is something wrong with time.

155
00:09:42,320 --> 00:09:44,520
-You mentioned a woman.
-Yes.

156
00:09:45,560 --> 00:09:47,560
-I'm getting to her.
-What's she like?

157
00:09:47,880 --> 00:09:50,720
-Attractive, I assume?
-Hell...

158
00:09:51,520 --> 00:09:53,320
in high heels.

159
00:09:54,720 --> 00:09:55,720
Tell me more.

160
00:09:56,360 --> 00:09:58,440
Oh, it's not so bad, really.

161
00:09:58,520 --> 00:10:00,560
As long as they get your box
the right way up.

162
00:10:00,640 --> 00:10:02,960
I got a media chip fitted in my head
years ago

163
00:10:03,040 --> 00:10:05,320
and the Wi-Fi down here is excellent.

164
00:10:05,400 --> 00:10:07,000
So I keep myself entertained.

165
00:10:07,080 --> 00:10:09,600
-I need to know about the Silence.
-Oh.

166
00:10:10,960 --> 00:10:13,920
A religious order of great power
and discretion.

167
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:16,800
The sentinels of history,
as they like to call themselves.

168
00:10:16,880 --> 00:10:18,120
And they want me dead?

169
00:10:18,200 --> 00:10:21,600
No, not really. They just don't want
you to remain alive.

170
00:10:21,680 --> 00:10:23,800
That's okay, then.
I was a bit worried for a minute there.

171
00:10:23,880 --> 00:10:27,320
You're a man with a long
and dangerous past.

172
00:10:27,480 --> 00:10:30,280
But your future is infinitely
more terrifying.

173
00:10:30,360 --> 00:10:32,360
The Silence believe it must be averted.

174
00:10:32,440 --> 00:10:35,320
You know, you could have told me
all this the last time we met.

175
00:10:35,400 --> 00:10:38,040
(SIGHS) It was a busy day
and I got beheaded.

176
00:10:39,120 --> 00:10:42,240
What's so dangerous about my future?

177
00:10:42,640 --> 00:10:45,960
On the Fields of Trenzalor
at the fall of the Eleventh,

178
00:10:46,120 --> 00:10:49,640
when no living creature could speak
falsely or fail to answer,

179
00:10:49,720 --> 00:10:51,520
a question will be asked.

180
00:10:52,160 --> 00:10:55,600
A question that must never,
ever be answered.

181
00:10:56,040 --> 00:10:58,360
"Silence will fall
when the question is asked."

182
00:10:58,440 --> 00:11:01,200
"Silence must fall"
would be a better translation.

183
00:11:01,280 --> 00:11:04,320
The Silence are determined that
the question will never be answered,

184
00:11:04,400 --> 00:11:06,920
that the Doctor
will never reach Trenzalor.

185
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:08,880
I don't understand.
What's it got to do with me?

186
00:11:08,960 --> 00:11:10,360
The first question.

187
00:11:10,640 --> 00:11:14,320
The oldest question in the universe,
hidden in plain sight.

188
00:11:15,040 --> 00:11:17,240
-Would you like to know what it is?
-Yes.

189
00:11:17,320 --> 00:11:18,320
Are you sure?

190
00:11:27,520 --> 00:11:28,800
Very, very sure?

191
00:11:32,680 --> 00:11:33,680
Of course.

192
00:11:33,760 --> 00:11:35,120
Then I shall tell you.

193
00:11:35,600 --> 00:11:38,560
But on your own head be it.

194
00:11:38,760 --> 00:11:40,160
(CHUCKLING)

195
00:11:42,560 --> 00:11:44,920
It's not my fault. Put me back!

196
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:46,520
Ow!

197
00:11:46,600 --> 00:11:48,560
I've fallen on my nose!

198
00:11:56,240 --> 00:12:00,280
Have you got Wi-Fi here? I'm bored
already. And my nose is hurting.

199
00:12:01,160 --> 00:12:03,400
We all have to die, Doctor.

200
00:12:03,960 --> 00:12:06,520
But you more than most.
You do see that, don't you?

201
00:12:07,160 --> 00:12:09,480
You know what the question is now.

202
00:12:09,600 --> 00:12:12,000
You do see that you have to die.

203
00:12:12,800 --> 00:12:16,800
But what was the question?
Why did it mean your death?

204
00:12:19,960 --> 00:12:23,320
Suppose there was a man
who knew a secret,

205
00:12:23,440 --> 00:12:28,000
a terrible, dangerous secret
that must never be told?

206
00:12:29,920 --> 00:12:32,200
How would you erase that secret
from the world,

207
00:12:32,280 --> 00:12:35,160
destroy it forever,
before it can be spoken?

208
00:12:38,080 --> 00:12:39,480
If I had to,

209
00:12:39,880 --> 00:12:41,520
I'd destroy the man.

210
00:12:41,600 --> 00:12:43,480
And Silence would fall.

211
00:12:45,200 --> 00:12:48,880
All the times I've heard those words,
I never realised it was my silence.

212
00:12:50,160 --> 00:12:51,160
My death.

213
00:12:53,080 --> 00:12:54,800
The Doctor will fall.

214
00:13:00,400 --> 00:13:02,560
-Why are we here?
-This?

215
00:13:03,640 --> 00:13:06,640
-This is the senate room.
-Why did we leave your office?

216
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:10,200
Well, we wanted to stroll, didn't we?

217
00:13:11,640 --> 00:13:15,360
I think I've been running.
Why do you have your revolver?

218
00:13:15,440 --> 00:13:16,440
Well...

219
00:13:17,920 --> 00:13:20,720
you're dangerous company, soothsayer.

220
00:13:25,160 --> 00:13:26,160
Yes.

221
00:13:28,080 --> 00:13:30,080
I think I am.

222
00:13:30,160 --> 00:13:31,520
Resume your story?

223
00:13:32,240 --> 00:13:33,280
Doctor.

224
00:13:33,360 --> 00:13:35,960
Please. Open my hatch.

225
00:13:36,200 --> 00:13:37,680
I've got an awful headache.

226
00:13:38,240 --> 00:13:40,480
Which, to be honest,
means more than it used to.

227
00:13:41,360 --> 00:13:45,000
It's like some terrible weight
pressing down on my...

228
00:13:46,680 --> 00:13:48,560
Oh. I see.

229
00:13:49,480 --> 00:13:53,640
Why Lake Silencio? Why Utah?

230
00:13:53,720 --> 00:13:55,920
It's a still point in time.

231
00:13:56,760 --> 00:13:58,880
Makes it easier to create a fixed point.

232
00:13:58,960 --> 00:14:02,360
And your death is a fixed point, Doctor.
You can't run away from this.

233
00:14:02,440 --> 00:14:04,240
Been running all my life,
why should I stop?

234
00:14:04,320 --> 00:14:07,200
Because now you know what's at stake,
why your life must end.

235
00:14:07,280 --> 00:14:08,320
Not today.

236
00:14:08,400 --> 00:14:11,800
What's the point in delaying?
How long have you delayed already?

237
00:14:11,880 --> 00:14:13,440
Been knocking about,
bit of a farewell tour.

238
00:14:13,520 --> 00:14:15,600
Things to do. People to see.
There's always more.

239
00:14:15,680 --> 00:14:18,800
I can invent a new colour.
Save the dodo. Join the Beatles.

240
00:14:18,880 --> 00:14:21,360
Hello! It's me. Get him. Tell him
we're going out and it's all on me

241
00:14:21,440 --> 00:14:24,640
except for the money and the driving.
I have got a time machine,

242
00:14:24,720 --> 00:14:27,040
Dorium, it's all still going on.
For me, it never stops.

243
00:14:27,120 --> 00:14:29,920
Liz I is still waiting in a glade
to elope with me.

244
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:31,600
I could help Rose Tyler
with her homework.

245
00:14:31,680 --> 00:14:33,840
I could go on all Jack's stag parties
in one night...

246
00:14:33,920 --> 00:14:35,880
Time catches up with us all, Doctor.

247
00:14:35,960 --> 00:14:38,760
Well, it has never laid a glove on me!

248
00:14:40,440 --> 00:14:42,520
-Hello?
-Doctor, I'm so sorry.

249
00:14:43,200 --> 00:14:45,600
We didn't know how to contact you.

250
00:14:45,680 --> 00:14:48,960
I'm afraid Brigadier Lethbridge-Stewart
passed away.

251
00:14:49,040 --> 00:14:50,880
A few months ago.

252
00:14:51,360 --> 00:14:53,760
-Doctor?
-(STUTTERS) Yeah...

253
00:14:53,840 --> 00:14:56,120
-Yes, yes, er...
-It was very peaceful.

254
00:14:56,200 --> 00:14:58,520
He talked a lot about you,
if that's any comfort.

255
00:14:58,600 --> 00:15:00,480
Always made us pour an extra brandy

256
00:15:00,560 --> 00:15:02,760
in case you came round
one of these days.

257
00:15:03,080 --> 00:15:04,920
Doctor, what's wrong?

258
00:15:07,280 --> 00:15:08,520
Nothing, I...

259
00:15:09,200 --> 00:15:10,400
just...

260
00:15:26,800 --> 00:15:28,160
It's time.

261
00:15:33,200 --> 00:15:34,520
It's time.

262
00:15:39,760 --> 00:15:42,280
Surely you could deliver the messages
yourself?

263
00:15:42,360 --> 00:15:44,720
It would involve crossing
my own time stream.

264
00:15:46,360 --> 00:15:47,360
Best not.

265
00:15:47,440 --> 00:15:49,800
According to our files,
this is the end for you.

266
00:15:49,880 --> 00:15:51,160
Your final journey.

267
00:15:52,680 --> 00:15:55,280
We'll deliver your messages.
You can depend on us.

268
00:15:58,600 --> 00:15:59,600
Thank you.

269
00:16:04,360 --> 00:16:05,560
Doctor?

270
00:16:06,400 --> 00:16:08,520
Whatever you think of the Tesselecta,

271
00:16:08,600 --> 00:16:12,040
we are champions of law and order,
just as you've always been.

272
00:16:12,400 --> 00:16:14,120
Is there nothing else we can do?

273
00:16:20,120 --> 00:16:22,000
CHURCHILL: Why would you do this?

274
00:16:22,080 --> 00:16:25,200
Of all the things you've told me,
this I find hardest to believe.

275
00:16:25,280 --> 00:16:28,200
Why would you invite your friends
to see your death?

276
00:16:29,080 --> 00:16:30,520
If I had to die,

277
00:16:31,520 --> 00:16:33,120
I didn't have to die alone.

278
00:16:33,200 --> 00:16:36,000
-Doctor!
-(LAUGHING) It's the Pond!

279
00:16:36,120 --> 00:16:40,360
DOCTOR: Amy and Rory. The Last Centurion
and the girl who waited.

280
00:16:41,320 --> 00:16:45,680
However dark it got,
I'd turn around and there they'd be.

281
00:16:45,920 --> 00:16:48,440
If it's time to go,

282
00:16:49,040 --> 00:16:50,960
remember what you're leaving.

283
00:16:51,320 --> 00:16:53,120
Remember the best.

284
00:16:53,200 --> 00:16:55,280
My friends have always been
the best of me.

285
00:16:55,360 --> 00:16:57,240
And did you tell them
this was going to happen?

286
00:16:57,320 --> 00:17:00,040
It would help if you didn't keep
asking questions.

287
00:17:04,280 --> 00:17:06,160
(WHISPERING) We don't have much time.

288
00:17:06,640 --> 00:17:08,240
(GUNSHOT FIRING)

289
00:17:09,080 --> 00:17:10,880
CHURCHILL: And this woman you spoke of,

290
00:17:10,960 --> 00:17:12,080
did you invite her?

291
00:17:12,560 --> 00:17:13,760
Hello, sweetie.

292
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:15,640
DOCTOR: Yes, she was there.

293
00:17:16,440 --> 00:17:18,160
River Song came twice.

294
00:17:19,520 --> 00:17:21,560
Napoleon gave me this bottle.

295
00:17:22,280 --> 00:17:25,760
Well, I mean, I said "gave". Threw.

296
00:17:25,880 --> 00:17:27,080
Salut!

297
00:17:27,160 --> 00:17:28,560
ALL: Salut!

298
00:17:28,920 --> 00:17:31,320
So, when are we going to 19697

299
00:17:31,400 --> 00:17:33,040
DOCTOR: Everything was in place.

300
00:17:33,480 --> 00:17:35,400
I only had to do one more thing.

301
00:17:36,080 --> 00:17:37,520
I only had to die.

302
00:17:37,600 --> 00:17:39,000
Oh, my God!

303
00:17:40,720 --> 00:17:42,640
You all need to stay back.

304
00:17:43,760 --> 00:17:46,520
Whatever happens now,
you do not interfere.

305
00:17:50,920 --> 00:17:52,320
RORY: That's an astronaut.

306
00:17:53,160 --> 00:17:55,800
-That's an Apollo astronaut in the lake.
-Look...

307
00:18:07,560 --> 00:18:09,000
Well, then.

308
00:18:10,600 --> 00:18:11,640
Here we are at last.

309
00:18:12,320 --> 00:18:15,320
I can't stop it. The suit's in control.

310
00:18:15,480 --> 00:18:17,200
You're not supposed to.
This has to happen.

311
00:18:17,280 --> 00:18:19,120
-Run!
-I did run.

312
00:18:19,200 --> 00:18:22,680
-Running brought me here
-I tried to fight it, but I can't.

313
00:18:22,760 --> 00:18:24,640
-It's too strong.
-I know.

314
00:18:24,720 --> 00:18:26,000
It's okay.

315
00:18:27,160 --> 00:18:28,920
This is where I die.

316
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:32,760
This is a fixed point. This must happen.
This always happens.

317
00:18:33,280 --> 00:18:34,680
Don't worry.

318
00:18:35,160 --> 00:18:37,360
You won't even remember this.

319
00:18:40,200 --> 00:18:41,800
Look over there.

320
00:18:44,400 --> 00:18:45,920
It's me.

321
00:18:46,480 --> 00:18:48,200
How can I be there?

322
00:18:48,960 --> 00:18:50,360
That's you from the future,

323
00:18:51,800 --> 00:18:55,240
serving time for a murder
you probably can't remember.

324
00:18:56,320 --> 00:18:58,800
-My murder.
-Why would you do that?

325
00:18:59,800 --> 00:19:02,720
-Make me watch?
-So that you know this is inevitable.

326
00:19:04,400 --> 00:19:06,200
And you are forgiven.

327
00:19:06,600 --> 00:19:08,680
Always and completely forgiven.

328
00:19:08,800 --> 00:19:10,840
Please, my love.
Please, please, just run.

329
00:19:10,920 --> 00:19:12,560
-Can't.
-Time can be rewritten.

330
00:19:12,640 --> 00:19:14,320
Don't you dare.

331
00:19:15,760 --> 00:19:16,960
Goodbye, River.

332
00:19:24,960 --> 00:19:26,560
(RIVER GRUNTING)

333
00:19:36,680 --> 00:19:38,240
Hello, sweetie.

334
00:19:38,680 --> 00:19:39,960
What have you done?

335
00:19:40,120 --> 00:19:43,240
Well, I think I just drained
my weapon systems.

336
00:19:43,320 --> 00:19:44,720
But it's fixed.

337
00:19:44,800 --> 00:19:47,920
-This is a fixed point in time.
-Fixed points can be rewritten.

338
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:50,640
No, they can't. Of course they can't.
Who told you?

339
00:19:55,000 --> 00:19:56,800
Well, what happened?

340
00:19:57,200 --> 00:19:58,560
-Nothing.
-Nothing?

341
00:19:58,640 --> 00:20:00,680
Nothing happened.
And then it kept happening.

342
00:20:00,760 --> 00:20:05,480
Or, if you'd prefer, everything happened
at once and it won't ever stop.

343
00:20:05,760 --> 00:20:10,720
Time is dying. It's going to be 5:02
in the afternoon for all eternity.

344
00:20:11,600 --> 00:20:14,280
-The needle's stuck on a record.
-A record?

345
00:20:14,360 --> 00:20:17,080
Good Lord, man,
have you never heard of downloads?

346
00:20:17,280 --> 00:20:18,520
Said Winston Churchill.

347
00:20:18,600 --> 00:20:21,880
(SNIFFING) Gun smoke. That's gun smoke.

348
00:20:22,480 --> 00:20:25,200
Oh, I appeared to have fired this.

349
00:20:25,280 --> 00:20:28,480
-We seem to be defending ourselves.
-I don't understand.

350
00:20:28,600 --> 00:20:32,160
The creatures that lead the Silence,
remarkable beings, they're memory-proof.

351
00:20:32,240 --> 00:20:34,680
-But what does that mean?
-Well, you can't remember them.

352
00:20:34,760 --> 00:20:37,600
The moment you look away,
you forget they were ever there.

353
00:20:40,680 --> 00:20:42,400
Don't panic.

354
00:20:42,480 --> 00:20:44,520
In small numbers,
they're not too difficult.

355
00:20:48,400 --> 00:20:50,080
(CHITTERING)

356
00:20:56,160 --> 00:20:58,160
(BEEPING)

357
00:21:00,280 --> 00:21:01,360
Go!

358
00:21:01,440 --> 00:21:03,520
-(SCREAMING)
-Go! Go! Go!

359
00:21:04,680 --> 00:21:08,280
Keep the Silence in sight at all times.
And keep your eye drives active.

360
00:21:08,360 --> 00:21:10,720
Who the devil are you?
Identify yourselves.

361
00:21:10,800 --> 00:21:12,000
Pond.

362
00:21:12,400 --> 00:21:13,640
Amelia Pond.

363
00:21:13,720 --> 00:21:14,760
(LAUGHING)

364
00:21:14,840 --> 00:21:17,120
No! She's on our side.
It's okay, Winston.

365
00:21:20,200 --> 00:21:21,800
DOCTOR: (WHISPERING) No.

366
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:23,400
No, Amy.

367
00:21:23,880 --> 00:21:25,360
Amy.

368
00:21:26,360 --> 00:21:27,880
Why are you wearing the...

369
00:21:32,040 --> 00:21:35,160
MAN: The government is again apologising
for extensive radio interference

370
00:21:35,240 --> 00:21:38,040
caused by solar flare
and sunspot activity.

371
00:21:47,120 --> 00:21:48,200
Amy.

372
00:21:48,600 --> 00:21:52,880
Those stun guns aren't fun, I'm sorry.
I wanted to avoid a long conversation.

373
00:21:52,960 --> 00:21:55,200
You need to get up, though,
we'll be in Cairo shortly.

374
00:21:55,280 --> 00:21:56,280
Amy Pond.

375
00:21:56,600 --> 00:21:59,320
Amelia Pond from Leadworth,
please, listen to me.

376
00:21:59,680 --> 00:22:02,080
I know it seems impossible,
but you know me.

377
00:22:02,520 --> 00:22:05,080
In another version of reality,
you and I were best friends.

378
00:22:05,160 --> 00:22:08,400
We... We travelled together.
We had adventures.

379
00:22:08,480 --> 00:22:09,800
(GRUNTING)

380
00:22:10,560 --> 00:22:11,680
Amelia Pond.

381
00:22:11,800 --> 00:22:14,120
You grew up with a time rift
in the wall of your bedroom.

382
00:22:14,200 --> 00:22:18,040
You can see what others can't. You can
remember things that never happened.

383
00:22:18,120 --> 00:22:22,080
And if you try, if you really,
really try, you'll be able to...

384
00:22:24,160 --> 00:22:25,240
Oh.

385
00:22:28,320 --> 00:22:29,440
Oh!

386
00:22:32,600 --> 00:22:33,720
Oh!

387
00:22:39,720 --> 00:22:41,200
You look rubbish.

388
00:22:41,280 --> 00:22:42,720
You look wonderful.

389
00:22:42,800 --> 00:22:44,760
So do you. But don't worry.

390
00:22:46,760 --> 00:22:48,720
-We'll soon fix that.
-Oh.

391
00:22:48,800 --> 00:22:49,800
(LAUGHING)

392
00:22:50,240 --> 00:22:51,840
Geronimo!

393
00:22:54,320 --> 00:22:56,480
Okay, you can turn around now.
How do I look?

394
00:22:56,560 --> 00:22:57,840
-Cool.
-Really?

395
00:22:57,920 --> 00:22:59,880
-No.
-Cool office, though.

396
00:22:59,960 --> 00:23:03,360
Why do you have an office? Are you like
a special agent boss lady or something?

397
00:23:03,440 --> 00:23:06,320
-Not sure about the eye patch, though.
-It's not an eye patch.

398
00:23:06,400 --> 00:23:08,120
Time's gone wrong. Some of us noticed.

399
00:23:08,200 --> 00:23:10,440
There's a whole team of us
working on it. You'll see.

400
00:23:10,520 --> 00:23:13,320
And you've got an office on a train!
That is so cool!

401
00:23:13,400 --> 00:23:15,800
Can I have an office?
Never had an office before. Or a train.

402
00:23:15,880 --> 00:23:17,240
Or a train/office.

403
00:23:17,320 --> 00:23:18,640
God, I've missed you!

404
00:23:18,720 --> 00:23:21,240
Okay, hugging and missing now.

405
00:23:21,680 --> 00:23:23,480
-Where's the Roman?
-You mean Rory?

406
00:23:23,560 --> 00:23:26,520
-DOCTOR: Mmm.
-My husband, Rory, yeah? Um...

407
00:23:26,640 --> 00:23:28,960
That's him, isn't it? I have no idea.

408
00:23:29,040 --> 00:23:32,160
I can't find him.
I love him very much, don't I?

409
00:23:32,240 --> 00:23:33,400
Apparently.

410
00:23:33,480 --> 00:23:35,520
I have to keep doing this.
Writing and drawing things.

411
00:23:35,600 --> 00:23:37,600
It's just so hard to keep remembering.

412
00:23:37,680 --> 00:23:39,200
But it's not your fault.

413
00:23:39,280 --> 00:23:40,920
Time's gone wrong.

414
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:42,720
Do you remember why?

415
00:23:42,800 --> 00:23:45,280
-Lakeside.
-Lake Silencio, Utah. I died.

416
00:23:45,360 --> 00:23:47,800
But then you didn't die. See,
I remember it twice, different ways.

417
00:23:47,880 --> 00:23:49,760
Two different versions
of the same event,

418
00:23:49,840 --> 00:23:51,440
both happening in the same moment.

419
00:23:51,520 --> 00:23:54,040
Time split wide open. Now look at it.

420
00:23:55,160 --> 00:23:57,280
All of history happening at once.

421
00:23:57,920 --> 00:24:01,240
But does it matter?
I mean, can't we just stay like this?

422
00:24:01,320 --> 00:24:05,240
Time isn't just frozen.
It's disintegrating.

423
00:24:06,640 --> 00:24:11,440
It will spread and spread and
all of reality will simply fall apart.

424
00:24:11,880 --> 00:24:13,160
(DOOR OPENING)

425
00:24:13,360 --> 00:24:15,200
Ma'am, we're about to arrive.

426
00:24:15,280 --> 00:24:17,680
Eye drives need to be activated
as soon as we disembark.

427
00:24:17,760 --> 00:24:20,440
Good point.
Thank you, Captain Williams.

428
00:24:20,920 --> 00:24:22,120
Hello.

429
00:24:22,360 --> 00:24:24,240
Hello, sir. Pleased to meet you.

430
00:24:24,320 --> 00:24:27,760
Captain Williams, best of the best.
Couldn't live without him.

431
00:24:28,720 --> 00:24:30,760
(LAUGHING) No!

432
00:24:30,840 --> 00:24:32,200
What is wrong?

433
00:24:32,280 --> 00:24:35,160
Amy, you'll find your Rory,
you always do.

434
00:24:35,240 --> 00:24:37,880
-But you really have to look.
-I am looking!

435
00:24:37,960 --> 00:24:40,720
Oh, my Amelia Pond,

436
00:24:41,360 --> 00:24:42,960
you don't always look hard enough.

437
00:24:43,040 --> 00:24:44,600
Why are you older?

438
00:24:44,680 --> 00:24:47,960
If time isn't really passing,
then how can you be ageing?

439
00:24:48,040 --> 00:24:50,320
Time is still passing for me.

440
00:24:50,400 --> 00:24:52,680
Every explosion has an epicentre.

441
00:24:53,400 --> 00:24:54,640
I'm it.

442
00:24:55,440 --> 00:24:56,520
I'm what's wrong.

443
00:24:56,600 --> 00:24:58,440
What's wrong with you?

444
00:25:04,840 --> 00:25:06,480
I'm still alive.

445
00:25:23,440 --> 00:25:24,720
You have to put it on, sir.

446
00:25:24,800 --> 00:25:26,160
An eye patch? What for?

447
00:25:26,240 --> 00:25:28,240
-It's not an eye patch.
-It's an eye drive, sir.

448
00:25:28,320 --> 00:25:31,000
It communicates directly with the
memory centres of the brain.

449
00:25:31,080 --> 00:25:32,560
Acts as external storage.

450
00:25:32,640 --> 00:25:34,040
Only thing that works on them.

451
00:25:34,120 --> 00:25:36,920
Because no living mind
can remember these things.

452
00:25:38,200 --> 00:25:39,800
The Silence,

453
00:25:39,880 --> 00:25:41,840
we've captured over a hundred
of them now.

454
00:25:41,920 --> 00:25:43,800
All held in this pyramid.

455
00:25:43,880 --> 00:25:46,280
Yeah, I've encountered them before.

456
00:25:47,560 --> 00:25:48,960
Always wondered what they looked like?

457
00:25:49,040 --> 00:25:51,240
AMY: Well, put your eye drive on
and you'll retain the information,

458
00:25:51,320 --> 00:25:53,080
but only for as long
as you're wearing it.

459
00:25:53,160 --> 00:25:55,520
The Silence have human servants,
they all wear these?

460
00:25:55,600 --> 00:25:57,160
-They'd have to.
-This way.

461
00:25:58,520 --> 00:25:59,840
(CLICKING)

462
00:26:01,640 --> 00:26:03,840
They seem to be noticing you.

463
00:26:04,120 --> 00:26:05,760
Yeah, they would.

464
00:26:06,920 --> 00:26:09,280
So why aren't the human race
killing the Silence on sight any more?

465
00:26:09,360 --> 00:26:12,120
That was a whole other reality.
What are the tanks for?

466
00:26:12,200 --> 00:26:14,720
They can draw electricity from anything,
it's how they attack.

467
00:26:14,800 --> 00:26:15,880
The fluid insulates them

468
00:26:15,960 --> 00:26:18,440
and I really don't like the way
they're looking at you.

469
00:26:18,520 --> 00:26:20,240
-Me, neither.
-Ma'am.

470
00:26:20,520 --> 00:26:22,200
I'm sure it's nothing,
but I should really check this out.

471
00:26:22,280 --> 00:26:24,080
They haven't been this active
in a while.

472
00:26:24,160 --> 00:26:26,120
You two, upstairs.
Check all the tank seals.

473
00:26:26,200 --> 00:26:28,240
Then the floors above.
Get everyone checking.

474
00:26:28,320 --> 00:26:29,400
Sir.

475
00:26:31,080 --> 00:26:32,560
-You go ahead, ma'am.
-Thank you, Captain Williams.

476
00:26:32,640 --> 00:26:34,040
Doctor, this way.

477
00:26:34,120 --> 00:26:36,360
DOCTOR: Captain Williams, nice fella.

478
00:26:36,440 --> 00:26:38,520
-What's his first name?
-Captain. Just through here.

479
00:26:38,600 --> 00:26:42,600
Just, uh, give us a moment.
Just need to check something, ma'am.

480
00:26:45,080 --> 00:26:47,080
We're in. He's on his way.

481
00:26:48,680 --> 00:26:52,360
Loyal soldier, waiting to be noticed.
Always the pattern. Why is that?

482
00:26:52,440 --> 00:26:53,520
Sorry, sir?

483
00:26:53,600 --> 00:26:57,120
Your boss, you should just ask her out.
She likes you. She said so.

484
00:26:57,960 --> 00:26:59,360
Really, sir?

485
00:27:01,760 --> 00:27:03,400
CAPTAIN: What did she say?

486
00:27:04,320 --> 00:27:07,280
Oh, she just sort of
generally indicated.

487
00:27:07,360 --> 00:27:09,440
-What exactly did she say?
-She said that

488
00:27:09,520 --> 00:27:12,080
you were a Mr Hottie...ness.

489
00:27:12,520 --> 00:27:15,560
And that she would like to
go out with you for

490
00:27:16,200 --> 00:27:17,880
texting and scones.

491
00:27:20,480 --> 00:27:22,160
You really haven't done this
before, have you?

492
00:27:22,240 --> 00:27:23,760
No, I haven't.

493
00:27:28,080 --> 00:27:30,160
See you in a moment, sir.

494
00:27:30,240 --> 00:27:31,480
Yes.

495
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:35,280
Yes.

496
00:27:37,320 --> 00:27:40,800
Come on, Doctor. Time for you
to meet some old friends.

497
00:27:41,200 --> 00:27:42,840
Attention, all personnel.

498
00:27:42,920 --> 00:27:45,240
Attention, all personnel.

499
00:27:45,320 --> 00:27:47,800
Please check all the site
containment units.

500
00:27:47,880 --> 00:27:49,000
You were right.

501
00:27:49,080 --> 00:27:50,880
Just his presence in the building
caused the loop to extend

502
00:27:50,960 --> 00:27:53,040
by nearly four cronons.

503
00:27:53,120 --> 00:27:54,800
(BEEPING)

504
00:27:54,880 --> 00:27:56,640
Hi, honey, I'm home.

505
00:27:57,280 --> 00:27:59,960
And what sort of time do you call this?

506
00:28:00,400 --> 00:28:02,080
The death of time.

507
00:28:02,360 --> 00:28:03,960
The end of time.

508
00:28:04,520 --> 00:28:06,160
The end of us all.

509
00:28:06,240 --> 00:28:08,280
Oh, why couldn't you just die?

510
00:28:08,360 --> 00:28:12,520
Did my best, dear, I showed up. You just
can't get the psychopaths these days.

511
00:28:12,800 --> 00:28:15,200
Love what you've done with the pyramids!

512
00:28:15,280 --> 00:28:16,640
How did you swing all this?

513
00:28:16,720 --> 00:28:19,880
Hallucinogenic lipstick.
Works wonders on President Kennedy.

514
00:28:19,960 --> 00:28:21,960
And Cleopatra was a real pushover.

515
00:28:22,040 --> 00:28:23,760
-I always thought so.
-She mentioned you.

516
00:28:23,840 --> 00:28:25,600
-What did she say?
-"Put down that gun.”

517
00:28:25,680 --> 00:28:27,040
-Did you?
-Eventually.

518
00:28:27,120 --> 00:28:29,160
Oh, they're flirting.
Do I have to watch this?

519
00:28:29,240 --> 00:28:32,280
It was such a basic mistake,
wasn't it, Madame Kovarian?

520
00:28:32,360 --> 00:28:34,960
Take a child, raise her into
a perfect psychopath,

521
00:28:35,040 --> 00:28:37,200
introduce her to the Doctor.

522
00:28:37,480 --> 00:28:39,520
Who else was I
going to fall in love with?

523
00:28:39,600 --> 00:28:41,920
That's not funny, River.
Reality is fatally compromised.

524
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:43,720
Tell me you understand that.

525
00:28:43,800 --> 00:28:45,000
-Dinner?
-I don't have the time.

526
00:28:45,080 --> 00:28:46,880
Nobody has the time.
Because as long as I'm alive,

527
00:28:46,960 --> 00:28:50,160
time is dying, because of you, River.

528
00:28:50,240 --> 00:28:51,960
Because I refuse to kill the man I love.

529
00:28:52,040 --> 00:28:53,760
Oh, you love me, do you?
Aw, that's sweet of you...

530
00:28:53,840 --> 00:28:55,840
-Get him!
-Come here, you.

531
00:28:56,880 --> 00:29:00,120
I'm not a fool, sweetie.
I know what happens if we touch.

532
00:29:03,400 --> 00:29:04,480
Get off me!

533
00:29:04,560 --> 00:29:07,800
Get him off me! Doctor, no, let go!
Please. Let go!

534
00:29:07,880 --> 00:29:09,600
Moving...

535
00:29:09,680 --> 00:29:11,920
-Time's moving!
-Get him off me!

536
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:14,320
-Doctor!
-I'm sorry, River, it's the only way.

537
00:29:21,560 --> 00:29:22,720
Ah!

538
00:29:25,800 --> 00:29:27,120
Cuff him!

539
00:29:27,280 --> 00:29:29,640
Oh, why do you always have handcuffs?

540
00:29:29,720 --> 00:29:32,360
It's the only way, River. We're the
opposite poles of the disruption.

541
00:29:32,440 --> 00:29:35,560
If we touch, we short out the
differential. Time can begin again.

542
00:29:35,640 --> 00:29:37,400
And I'll be by a lakeside, killing you.

543
00:29:37,480 --> 00:29:39,440
And time won't fall apart.
The clocks will tick.

544
00:29:39,520 --> 00:29:42,000
Reality will continue.
There isn't another way.

545
00:29:42,080 --> 00:29:44,280
I didn't say there was, sweetie.

546
00:29:52,920 --> 00:29:54,360
(CRACKING)

547
00:30:05,560 --> 00:30:06,760
(WATER DRIPPING)

548
00:30:16,920 --> 00:30:18,280
(ELECTRICITY CRACKLING)

549
00:30:21,920 --> 00:30:24,040
RIVER: There are so many theories
about you and I, you know?

550
00:30:24,120 --> 00:30:25,680
-Idle gossip.
-Archaeology.

551
00:30:25,760 --> 00:30:28,640
-Same thing!
-Am I the woman who marries you

552
00:30:28,800 --> 00:30:30,720
-or the woman who murders you?
-Oh.

553
00:30:31,480 --> 00:30:33,600
-I don't want to marry you.
-I don't want to murder you.

554
00:30:33,720 --> 00:30:35,320
-(WATER DRIPPING)
-DOCTOR: Well, this is no fun at all.

555
00:30:35,400 --> 00:30:36,480
It isn't, is it?

556
00:30:36,560 --> 00:30:38,800
Doctor, what's that?

557
00:30:44,480 --> 00:30:46,120
DOCTOR: The pyramid above us.

558
00:30:46,320 --> 00:30:48,640
How many Silence have you got
trapped inside it?

559
00:30:48,720 --> 00:30:52,680
None. They're not trapped.
They never have been.

560
00:30:53,720 --> 00:30:55,520
They've been waiting.

561
00:30:55,600 --> 00:30:57,200
For this, Doctor.

562
00:30:57,520 --> 00:30:58,600
For you.

563
00:30:59,160 --> 00:31:01,000
They're out! All of them!

564
00:31:01,080 --> 00:31:02,160
(CHITTERING)

565
00:31:03,680 --> 00:31:05,400
MAN: Fall back!

566
00:31:05,960 --> 00:31:07,200
(SCREAMING)

567
00:31:09,720 --> 00:31:11,120
(MEN SCREAMING)

568
00:31:13,200 --> 00:31:14,600
CAPTAIN: No one gets in here.

569
00:31:15,120 --> 00:31:17,160
Ma'am, my men out there
should be able to lock this down.

570
00:31:17,240 --> 00:31:18,320
We have them outnumbered.

571
00:31:18,400 --> 00:31:22,480
And you're wearing eye drives
based on mine, I think. Whoops.

572
00:31:22,560 --> 00:31:24,080
What do you mean?

573
00:31:24,960 --> 00:31:26,080
(SCREAMING)

574
00:31:26,160 --> 00:31:27,880
Help her! Help her!

575
00:31:29,320 --> 00:31:30,480
(SCREAMING)

576
00:31:31,120 --> 00:31:32,240
She's dead.

577
00:31:34,880 --> 00:31:36,280
MAN: Fall back now!

578
00:31:36,360 --> 00:31:37,680
(SCREAMING)

579
00:31:41,160 --> 00:31:42,880
(SCREAMING)

580
00:31:43,280 --> 00:31:45,560
Eye drives off now! Remove them!

581
00:31:45,680 --> 00:31:46,880
Ahh!

582
00:31:48,720 --> 00:31:49,800
Ahh!

583
00:31:49,880 --> 00:31:52,160
The Silence would
never allow an advantage

584
00:31:52,240 --> 00:31:54,320
without taking one themselves.

585
00:31:54,400 --> 00:31:56,920
The effects will vary
from person to person,

586
00:31:57,000 --> 00:32:00,400
either death or debilitating agony.

587
00:32:01,280 --> 00:32:04,360
But they will take you all, one by one.

588
00:32:06,560 --> 00:32:09,120
What are you doing? No, it's me.

589
00:32:10,840 --> 00:32:12,480
Don't be stupid!

590
00:32:13,120 --> 00:32:14,520
You need me.

591
00:32:16,160 --> 00:32:17,320
Stop it!

592
00:32:17,400 --> 00:32:18,480
Stop that!

593
00:32:18,560 --> 00:32:20,120
We can stop this right now, you and I.

594
00:32:20,200 --> 00:32:21,320
Get it off me!

595
00:32:21,400 --> 00:32:22,960
-Amy, tell her!
-We've been working on something.

596
00:32:23,040 --> 00:32:24,920
-Just let us show you.
-No point. There's nothing you can do.

597
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:26,400
-My time is up.
-We're doing this for you!

598
00:32:26,480 --> 00:32:29,120
And people are dying for me.
I won't thank you for that, Amelia Pond.

599
00:32:30,120 --> 00:32:32,320
-Just let us show you.
-Please!

600
00:32:34,120 --> 00:32:35,480
Captain Williams, how long do we have?

601
00:32:35,560 --> 00:32:37,320
Ah, a couple of minutes?

602
00:32:37,400 --> 00:32:39,040
That's enough.
We're going to the receptor room,

603
00:32:39,120 --> 00:32:40,640
right at the top of the pyramid.

604
00:32:40,720 --> 00:32:42,480
I hope you're ready for a climb.

605
00:32:42,560 --> 00:32:45,400
I'll wait down here, ma"am,
buy you as much time as I can.

606
00:32:45,480 --> 00:32:47,400
-You'll have to take your eye drive off.
-Can't do that, ma'am.

607
00:32:47,480 --> 00:32:49,520
-Can't forget what's coming.
-But it could activate any second.

608
00:32:49,600 --> 00:32:52,400
It has activated, ma'am.

609
00:32:52,840 --> 00:32:54,800
But I'm of no use to you
if I can't remember.

610
00:32:56,000 --> 00:32:57,680
You have to go now, ma'am!

611
00:32:57,760 --> 00:32:58,840
-Yes.
-Now.

612
00:32:58,920 --> 00:33:01,800
Yes. Thank you, Captain Williams.

613
00:33:03,360 --> 00:33:05,480
(BANGING ON DOOR)

614
00:33:17,840 --> 00:33:20,320
(SCREAMING)

615
00:33:24,000 --> 00:33:27,520
SILENT: Rory Williams,
the man who dies

616
00:33:27,600 --> 00:33:29,560
and dies again.

617
00:33:29,680 --> 00:33:32,040
Die one last time.

618
00:33:32,120 --> 00:33:36,200
And know she will
never come back for you.

619
00:33:42,680 --> 00:33:43,840
(RORY SCREAMING)

620
00:33:43,920 --> 00:33:46,400
Come on, you, up you get. You all right?

621
00:33:46,480 --> 00:33:47,640
(SHOUTING)

622
00:33:50,040 --> 00:33:52,840
Amy, help me.

623
00:33:55,040 --> 00:33:56,800
You took my baby from me.

624
00:33:56,880 --> 00:33:58,320
And hurt her.

625
00:33:58,400 --> 00:34:01,560
And now she's all grown up
and she's fine,

626
00:34:01,640 --> 00:34:03,520
but I'll never see my baby again.

627
00:34:03,600 --> 00:34:06,000
But you'll still save me, though.

628
00:34:07,360 --> 00:34:09,040
Because he would.

629
00:34:09,120 --> 00:34:14,360
And you'd never do anything to
disappoint your precious Doctor.

630
00:34:14,440 --> 00:34:16,240
Ma'am, we have to go, now!

631
00:34:16,320 --> 00:34:18,640
The Doctor is very precious to me,
you're right.

632
00:34:18,720 --> 00:34:21,600
But do you know what else he is,
Madame Kovarian?

633
00:34:23,520 --> 00:34:24,800
Not here.

634
00:34:25,600 --> 00:34:27,600
(GASPING) Ah!

635
00:34:28,280 --> 00:34:30,640
River Song didn't get it all from you,

636
00:34:30,720 --> 00:34:31,960
sweetie.

637
00:34:34,800 --> 00:34:35,880
(SCREAMING)

638
00:34:35,960 --> 00:34:37,640
So, you and me, we should
get a drink sometime.

639
00:34:37,720 --> 00:34:39,160
-Okay.
-I'm married.

640
00:34:39,240 --> 00:34:40,320
Fine.

641
00:34:41,240 --> 00:34:42,480
(MEN SCREAMING)

642
00:34:46,560 --> 00:34:50,240
What's this? Oh, it's a tiny-winy
distress beacon. Who built this?

643
00:34:50,320 --> 00:34:53,000
I'm in charge of the Tardis.
I understand the physics.

644
00:34:53,080 --> 00:34:55,240
Yes, but that's all you've got,
is a distress beacon?

645
00:34:55,320 --> 00:34:58,160
I've been sending out a message.
A distress call.

646
00:34:58,240 --> 00:35:01,120
Outside the bubble of our time,
the universe is still turning

647
00:35:01,200 --> 00:35:02,760
and I've sent a message everywhere.

648
00:35:02,840 --> 00:35:04,360
To the future and the past,

649
00:35:04,440 --> 00:35:06,560
the beginning and the end of everything.

650
00:35:06,640 --> 00:35:08,320
"The Doctor is dying,

651
00:35:08,400 --> 00:35:10,600
"please, please help."

652
00:35:10,680 --> 00:35:12,960
River! River, this is ridiculous!

653
00:35:13,040 --> 00:35:15,160
That would mean nothing to anyone.
It's insane!

654
00:35:15,240 --> 00:35:17,040
Worse, it's stupid!

655
00:35:18,280 --> 00:35:19,880
You embarrass me!

656
00:35:19,960 --> 00:35:23,280
We barricaded the door,
we've got a few minutes. Just tell him.

657
00:35:23,360 --> 00:35:24,800
Just tell him, River!

658
00:35:24,880 --> 00:35:27,240
Those reports of the sunspots
and the solar flares,

659
00:35:27,600 --> 00:35:29,680
they're wrong. There aren't any.

660
00:35:29,840 --> 00:35:32,000
It's not the sun. It's you.

661
00:35:32,080 --> 00:35:35,040
The sky is full
of a million, million voices

662
00:35:35,880 --> 00:35:39,040
saying, "Yes, of course. We'll help."

663
00:35:40,120 --> 00:35:43,400
You've touched so many lives,
saved so many people.

664
00:35:43,480 --> 00:35:45,440
Did you think when your time came

665
00:35:45,520 --> 00:35:48,360
you'd really have to do
more than just ask?

666
00:35:49,160 --> 00:35:52,480
You've decided that the universe
is better off without you.

667
00:35:52,560 --> 00:35:54,240
But the universe doesn't agree.

668
00:35:54,320 --> 00:35:57,360
River, no one can help me.

669
00:35:57,440 --> 00:36:01,080
A fixed point has been altered.
Time is disintegrating.

670
00:36:01,160 --> 00:36:02,480
I can't let you die!

671
00:36:02,560 --> 00:36:04,720
-But I have to die!
-Shut up!

672
00:36:05,800 --> 00:36:07,720
I can't let you die

673
00:36:08,800 --> 00:36:10,960
without knowing you are loved.

674
00:36:11,920 --> 00:36:13,960
By so many, and so much!

675
00:36:15,200 --> 00:36:17,240
And by no one more than me.

676
00:36:18,320 --> 00:36:21,120
River, you and I,
we know what this means.

677
00:36:21,360 --> 00:36:25,520
You know, we are ground zero of an
explosion that will engulf all reality.

678
00:36:25,600 --> 00:36:28,760
Billions on billions
will suffer and die.

679
00:36:28,840 --> 00:36:31,160
I'll suffer if I have to kill you.

680
00:36:31,240 --> 00:36:34,200
More than every living
thing in the universe?

681
00:36:38,880 --> 00:36:39,960
Yes.

682
00:36:46,240 --> 00:36:49,680
River, River. Why do you
have to be this?

683
00:36:50,080 --> 00:36:53,440
Melody Pond! Your daughter!
I hope you're both proud!

684
00:36:54,880 --> 00:36:56,320
I'm not sure I completely understand.

685
00:36:56,400 --> 00:36:59,440
Um, we got married
and had a kid and that's her.

686
00:36:59,520 --> 00:37:00,640
Okay.

687
00:37:03,760 --> 00:37:05,480
Amy, uncuff me now.

688
00:37:18,200 --> 00:37:21,640
Okay, I need a strip of cloth
about a foot long. Anything will do.

689
00:37:21,720 --> 00:37:24,360
Never mind. River, take one end of this.

690
00:37:25,120 --> 00:37:28,240
Wrap it around your hand
and hold it out to me.

691
00:37:28,400 --> 00:37:29,840
-What am I doing?
-As you're told.

692
00:37:29,920 --> 00:37:31,400
Now, we're in the middle
of a combat zone,

693
00:37:31,480 --> 00:37:32,920
so we'll have to do the quick version.

694
00:37:33,000 --> 00:37:36,200
Captain Williams, say,
"I consent and gladly give.”

695
00:37:36,400 --> 00:37:38,880
-To what?
-Just say it! Please.

696
00:37:39,640 --> 00:37:41,840
I consent and gladly give.

697
00:37:42,720 --> 00:37:44,560
Need you to say it, too.

698
00:37:45,520 --> 00:37:47,280
Mother of the bride.

699
00:37:47,560 --> 00:37:48,840
I consent and gladly give.

700
00:37:48,920 --> 00:37:52,000
Now, River, I am about to whisper
something in your ear

701
00:37:52,080 --> 00:37:54,640
and you have to remember it
very, very carefully

702
00:37:54,720 --> 00:37:57,680
and tell no one what I said.

703
00:38:07,440 --> 00:38:09,360
I just told you my name.

704
00:38:10,760 --> 00:38:13,880
Now, there you go, River Song,

705
00:38:14,720 --> 00:38:16,280
Melody Pond.

706
00:38:16,640 --> 00:38:18,600
You're the woman who married me.

707
00:38:19,840 --> 00:38:22,480
And, wife, I have a request.

708
00:38:23,560 --> 00:38:25,840
This world is dying and it's my fault.

709
00:38:25,920 --> 00:38:28,240
And I can't bear it another day.

710
00:38:28,640 --> 00:38:32,320
Please, help me.

711
00:38:34,560 --> 00:38:36,520
There isn't another way.

712
00:38:38,280 --> 00:38:40,360
Then you may kiss the bride.

713
00:38:40,840 --> 00:38:42,600
I'll make it a good one.

714
00:38:42,680 --> 00:38:44,080
You'd better.

715
00:39:11,800 --> 00:39:13,480
DOCTOR: And you are forgiven.

716
00:39:13,640 --> 00:39:16,000
Always and completely forgiven.

717
00:39:18,000 --> 00:39:20,320
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

718
00:39:20,920 --> 00:39:22,760
(CLOCKS CHIMING)

719
00:39:28,200 --> 00:39:31,600
CHILDREN: # Tick-tock goes the clock

720
00:39:31,680 --> 00:39:36,200
# He gave all he could give her

721
00:39:36,280 --> 00:39:39,720
# Tick-tock goes the clock

722
00:39:39,800 --> 00:39:43,120
# Now prison waits for River #

723
00:39:48,320 --> 00:39:49,960
(ELECTRICITY SURGING)

724
00:39:52,840 --> 00:39:55,760
Heard there was a freak
meteor shower two miles away.

725
00:39:55,840 --> 00:39:57,400
So I got us a bottle.

726
00:39:58,440 --> 00:40:00,040
Thank you, dear.

727
00:40:01,120 --> 00:40:02,720
So, where are we?

728
00:40:02,800 --> 00:40:05,280
I just climbed out of the Byzantium.

729
00:40:05,520 --> 00:40:07,640
You were there. So young.

730
00:40:08,560 --> 00:40:10,720
Didn't have a clue who I was.

731
00:40:10,800 --> 00:40:12,920
-Hmm?
-You're funny like that.

732
00:40:13,080 --> 00:40:15,000
Where are you?

733
00:40:17,400 --> 00:40:19,120
The Doctor is dead.

734
00:40:21,040 --> 00:40:22,720
How are you doing?

735
00:40:23,200 --> 00:40:24,840
How do you think?

736
00:40:25,160 --> 00:40:26,960
Well, I don't know, unless you tell me.

737
00:40:27,040 --> 00:40:28,680
I killed someone.

738
00:40:30,160 --> 00:40:31,760
Madame Kovarian.

739
00:40:32,480 --> 00:40:33,960
In cold blood.

740
00:40:34,400 --> 00:40:37,040
In an aborted timeline,
in a world that never was.

741
00:40:37,120 --> 00:40:40,720
Yeah, but I can remember it,
so it happened, so I did it.

742
00:40:43,600 --> 00:40:45,680
What does that make me now?

743
00:40:49,440 --> 00:40:52,840
I need to talk to the Doctor,
but I can't now, can I?

744
00:40:54,680 --> 00:40:57,400
If you could talk to him,
would it make a difference?

745
00:40:57,480 --> 00:40:59,640
He's dead so... So I can't.

746
00:41:00,040 --> 00:41:03,440
Oh, Mother! Of course he isn't!

747
00:41:04,960 --> 00:41:06,880
Not for you, I suppose.

748
00:41:07,160 --> 00:41:11,760
You're seeing the younger versions of
them, running around, having adventures.

749
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:13,640
Yeah, I am.

750
00:41:14,680 --> 00:41:16,600
But that's not what I mean.

751
00:41:16,720 --> 00:41:18,600
Then what do you mean?

752
00:41:20,280 --> 00:41:21,480
Okay,

753
00:41:22,680 --> 00:41:25,840
I'm going to tell you
what I probably shouldn't.

754
00:41:26,040 --> 00:41:28,040
The Doctor's last secret.

755
00:41:28,800 --> 00:41:31,000
Don't you want to know
what he whispered in my ear?

756
00:41:31,080 --> 00:41:33,040
-He whispered his name.
-Not his name, no.

757
00:41:33,120 --> 00:41:34,480
Yeah, it was. He said it was.

758
00:41:34,560 --> 00:41:36,920
-Rule one?
-The Doctor lies.

759
00:41:37,000 --> 00:41:39,240
So do I. All the time. Have to.

760
00:41:39,960 --> 00:41:41,480
Spoilers.

761
00:41:41,560 --> 00:41:43,200
Pretending I don't know
you're my mother,

762
00:41:43,280 --> 00:41:46,000
pretending I didn't recognise
a space suit in Florida.

763
00:41:46,080 --> 00:41:48,560
-What did he whisper in your ear?
-Oh...

764
00:41:49,520 --> 00:41:50,800
that man!

765
00:41:52,080 --> 00:41:54,880
He was always one step
ahead of everyone. Always a plan.

766
00:41:54,960 --> 00:41:57,640
River, what did he tell you?

767
00:41:58,960 --> 00:42:00,080
River?

768
00:42:00,160 --> 00:42:01,160
(LAUGHING)

769
00:42:01,240 --> 00:42:02,920
(AMY YELPING)

770
00:42:08,960 --> 00:42:10,000
Hey!

771
00:42:17,760 --> 00:42:19,600
(INDISTINCT)

772
00:42:19,840 --> 00:42:21,920
-(RIVER LAUGHING)
-Are you sure, River?

773
00:42:22,000 --> 00:42:25,080
-Are you really, properly sure?
-Of course I'm sure! I'm his wife!

774
00:42:25,160 --> 00:42:26,920
Yes! And I'm his...

775
00:42:27,200 --> 00:42:28,680
mother-in-law.

776
00:42:30,600 --> 00:42:33,760
Father, dear, I think Mummy
might need another drink.

777
00:42:33,840 --> 00:42:35,440
Yes, yes.

778
00:42:38,600 --> 00:42:40,680
DORIUM: Who's carrying me?

779
00:42:41,200 --> 00:42:42,840
I demand to know!

780
00:42:43,760 --> 00:42:45,760
I'm a head. I have rights!

781
00:42:47,720 --> 00:42:50,120
I want my doors open this time.

782
00:42:51,720 --> 00:42:54,040
I demand that my doors are open!

783
00:42:59,200 --> 00:43:01,640
Is it you? It is, isn't it?

784
00:43:02,840 --> 00:43:05,320
It is you. I can sense it!

785
00:43:06,280 --> 00:43:08,560
But how did you do it?

786
00:43:08,840 --> 00:43:11,360
How could you have possibly escaped?

787
00:43:11,680 --> 00:43:13,920
Is there nothing else we can do?

788
00:43:19,320 --> 00:43:21,200
Actually, thinking about it...

789
00:43:21,280 --> 00:43:22,920
Look into my eye.

790
00:43:28,560 --> 00:43:29,680
Shh!

791
00:43:37,920 --> 00:43:41,720
The Tesselecta.
A Doctor in a Doctor's suit.

792
00:43:42,360 --> 00:43:45,320
Time said I had to be on that beach,
so I dressed for the occasion.

793
00:43:45,400 --> 00:43:47,520
Barely got singed in that boat.

794
00:43:47,600 --> 00:43:49,960
So you're going to do this,
let them all think you're dead?

795
00:43:50,040 --> 00:43:51,640
It's the only way.
Then they can all forget me.

796
00:43:51,720 --> 00:43:54,320
I got too big, Dorium, too noisy.

797
00:43:55,680 --> 00:43:57,320
Time to step back into the shadows.

798
00:43:57,400 --> 00:44:00,400
And Dr Song? In prison all her days?

799
00:44:00,480 --> 00:44:02,520
Her days, yes. Her nights...

800
00:44:03,120 --> 00:44:06,440
Well, that's between her and me, eh?

801
00:44:06,520 --> 00:44:09,400
So many secrets, Doctor.

802
00:44:09,480 --> 00:44:11,400
I'll help you keep them, of course.

803
00:44:11,480 --> 00:44:13,080
Well, you're not exactly going anywhere,
are you?

804
00:44:13,160 --> 00:44:14,960
But you're a fool, nonetheless.

805
00:44:15,040 --> 00:44:16,880
It's all still waiting for you.

806
00:44:16,960 --> 00:44:19,880
The Fields of Trenzalor,
the fall of the Eleventh

807
00:44:19,960 --> 00:44:21,560
and the question.

808
00:44:22,160 --> 00:44:23,600
Goodbye, Dorium.

809
00:44:23,680 --> 00:44:25,400
The first question.

810
00:44:26,600 --> 00:44:29,360
The question that must
never be answered!

811
00:44:29,880 --> 00:44:31,720
Hidden in plain sight!

812
00:44:32,600 --> 00:44:36,520
The question you've been
running from all your life!

813
00:44:37,040 --> 00:44:38,480
Doctor who?

814
00:44:40,320 --> 00:44:41,960
Doctor who?

815
00:44:43,120 --> 00:44:45,680
Doctor who?

